Got it. The “Invalid Date” comes from rendering a date formatter (<FormattedDate />) with a value that isn’t a valid Date (often null, "", "None", or an invalid string). The clean/pro way is: validate first, then render either the formatted date or a placeholder like —.
✅ Recommended UX
Use an em dash — (looks more pro than ---).
Optionally add a tooltip “Not set”.
✅ Fix in your component (simple + solid)
Replace this part:
JSX
Copier le code
{initiative?.committeeDate ? (
  <FormattedDate
    value={initiative.committeeDate}
    month="short"
    year="numeric"
    day="2-digit"
  />
) : (
  <p>---</p>
)}
with:
JSX
Copier le code
const committeeDateValue = initiative?.committeeDate;
const committeeDate = committeeDateValue ? new Date(committeeDateValue) : null;
const hasValidCommitteeDate =
  committeeDate instanceof Date && !Number.isNaN(committeeDate.getTime());
and in JSX:
JSX
Copier le code
{hasValidCommitteeDate ? (
  <FormattedDate
    value={committeeDate}
    month="short"
    year="numeric"
    day="2-digit"
  />
) : (
  <span aria-label="Not set">—</span>
)}
✅ This prevents “Invalid Date” even if committeeDate is "None" or a bad string.
🔥 Even cleaner (reusable helper)
Add a small helper:
JSX
Copier le code
const safeDate = (value) => {
  if (!value) return null;
  const d = new Date(value);
  return Number.isNaN(d.getTime()) ? null : d;
};
Then:
